reviews.review_text:
most fun I didn't see a whole lot of shows, but this was probably the most fun. I was kind of uptight at the first show, because I had to rush to Red Rocks from work, and I was stressed about being able to find my friends. But for this one I had the whole day off and was nice and relaxed.

It was rainy when they let folks in, or it was threatening to rain. But right before the first set, the clouds parted over the hill behind the amphitheater. It was absolutely gorgeous. That's right when the acid kicked in.

My friends and I were all seated pretty high up, so we could see all of Denver off in the distance. 

All these years later, what I remember most is Bird Song and the Other One. Listening now again, I'm enjoying pretty much all of it. I'm only part way through the first set, but so far so good.

I have to say, it is so weird finding these recordings. I haven't tripped for more than 20 years. But listening to this, I can see that night, and feel it all over again. It's kind of exhilerating.
8-12-87 Nice. A nice C Miller remaster of a matrix recording.

Women ARE tarter I think only CB into MB and it works. I liked NTAW bc I just found out my gf at the time made out with my best friend at a Butthole Surfers show so it was like Brent knew exactly how I felt. Sad but lots of narcs. Saw one of the guys from Shaman Jam, the at the time Nation's #2 travelling drum circle get busted out in parking lot for smoking a bidi cop said was a joint.  Narcs and Touch Heads. I swear.

1st Dead Show It was my first.  It wasn't the best show I saw, but the whole experience so profoundly changed the course of my life that it is a before my first show and after.  I was 16 and had no idea what I was doing, but met some incredible people that welcomed me into the community like a family member they had always known.  It set me up for much adventure over the next 5 years scraping together what I could to see them play around the country.  I was lucky enough to see them in Paris in 1990.  I have to smile when I think back on all of the good times the band and the fans provided over the years.  Much love!
